\begin_layout Standard
Adaptive Regional Input-Output (ARIO) is an I-O model, designed to compute
 indirect costs from exogenous shocks.
 Its first version dates back to 2008 and has originally been developed
 to assess the indirect costs of natural disasters 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hallegatte08_adapt_region_input_output_model"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this paper we present BoARIO, a generic
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the sense that it is not specifically designed for this study.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 python implementation, similar to the one described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hallegatte13_model_role_inven_heter_asses"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with some additions (e.g.
 inspired by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "guan20_global_suppl_chain_effec_covid_contr_measur"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The economy is modelled as a set of economic sectors and a set of regions.
 In the following, we call an industry a specific (sector, region) couple.
 Each economic sector produces its generic product and draws inputs from
 an inventory.
 Each industry answers to a total demand consisting of a final demand (household
 consumption, public spending and private investments) coming from all regions
 (i.e.
 both local demand and exports), intermediate demand (inventory resupply).
 An initial equilibrium state of the economy is built based on multi-regional
 input-output tables (MRIOT).
 Apart from parameters specific to the MRIOT region-sector typology, BoARIO
 handles any MRIOT in the same manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiple kinds of shocks can be implemented:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On the production capacity directly (one or multiple industries are arbitrarily
 forced to produce less)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On the productive capital (one or multiple industries arbitrarily lose some
 part of their factors of production and are thus forced to both produce
 less and to build back their capital stock).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On the households (households of affected regions lose some part of their
 goods and seek to get them back).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model then describes how exogenous shocks propagates across the economy
 at each time step (a day in the present study
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Our implementation actually allows for any time granularity.
\end_layout

\end_inset

): the imbalance between production and demand is resolved by a proportional
 rationing scheme, which then leads some industries and households to not
 receive the totality of their orders.
 Industries can buffer these unfilled orders with their 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inventories
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of input and increase or shift their resupply demand.
 Currently, households simply register the loss as final consumption not
 met and do not postpone their demand.
 During the simulation, industries adjust their production and orders based
 on both demand and their inventories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Direct economic impact consists in the valuation of the initial exogenous
 shock, while total economic impact includes also indirect costs consequent
 to the propagation.
 Total economic impact can be measured in two ways:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Final demand not met, i.e.
 goods that households could not buy due to rationing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Relative production change, i.e.
 diminished or increased production of industries relative to their initial
 production.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study we focus on the second measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Detailed description
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.1.2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Initial state
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.1.2 init"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The initial state refers to an economic equilibrium before any exogenous
 shocks.
 Initial values for intermediate orders 
\begin_inset Formula $O(t=0)$
\end_inset

, final consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t=0)$
\end_inset

 and production 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t=0)$
\end_inset

 are derived from the MRIOT.
 Inventories 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(t)$
\end_inset

 are stocks of inputs an industry can draw into (see below for a detailed
 description of inventories) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(t=0)$
\end_inset

 are initialized using the initial intermediate orders: by default, it is
 assumed that every industry has a certain amount 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\textrm{input}}$
\end_inset

 of days of inputs ahead in their stocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Inventories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.1.2 invent"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In ARIO, economic sectors do not use inputs from other sectors directly,
 but draw inputs from inventories, that can then be re-supplied with intermediat
e orders 
\begin_inset Formula $O(t)$
\end_inset

.
 An industry's inventory is a vector that specifies how much of each product
 this industry has in stock.
 Each sector needs intermediate inputs in proportions given by the MRIOT
 at the initial state.
 Industries draw inputs from their inventories to try to produce at the
 optimal production level 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{Opt}}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 However, these inventories cannot be emptied: actual production 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{a}}(t)$
\end_inset

 can thus be set lower than optimal production 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{Opt}}(t)$
\end_inset

 to be sure that inventories are above a certain threshold (see Production
 for more details).
 Inventories have been implemented into ARIO to give a more realistic account
 of supply chain shocks, which can be mitigated by input stocks.
 The current state of an inventory for a definite input is expressed as
 the number of time steps a sector can produce with said input at current
 production level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Direct shocks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.1.2 shock"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Direct shocks are exogenous and can occur at any time step t.
 Conceptually, these shocks are the direct economic consequences of the
 events we are modelling.
 They can either be (i) direct production capacity losses or (ii) capital
 destruction.
 Capital is the only factor of production, so that in any industry 
\begin_inset Formula $x\%$
\end_inset

 capital destruction turns into 
\begin_inset Formula $x\%$
\end_inset

 production loss, as long as capital is not restored.
 There are two ways to model capital rebuilding:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Recovery Productive capital recovers from a purely exogenous function and
 at no cost for the economic agents: capital stock in a directly impacted
 industry goes back to its original level over time, following a chosen
 recovery curve, without any need for production sparing for rebuilding.
 This scenario can model the situation where capital is not actually destroyed
 but less available for instance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Rebuilding Productive capital is recovered through an endogenous rebuilding
 demand 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 which consists of new orders directed to sectors that usually provide capital
 stock: construction, transport equipment, manufacturing, etc.
 This additional demand leads to a reduction of actual production being
 allocated
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Such a reduction also happens in the Recovery case but to a lesser extent,
 as it only comes from the production reduction caused by the event
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to final demand 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

 or intermediate orders 
\begin_inset Formula $O(t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.1.2 prod"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production module computes actual production 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{a}}(t)$
\end_inset

 for each industry at the current time step with the following process:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It computes production capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{Cap}}(t)$
\end_inset

, which is production in the initial state 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t=0)$
\end_inset

 less production capacity reduction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It defines optimal production 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{Opt}}(t)$
\end_inset

 as the minimum between production capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{Cap}}(t)$
\end_inset

 and total demand 
\begin_inset Formula $O(t)+Y(t)+\Gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 : the model is demand-driven, and industries cannot produce more than total
 demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finally, the actual production 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{a}}(t)$
\end_inset

 is computed from 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{Opt}}(t)$
\end_inset

, taking into account inventories constraints.
 More precisely, an industry can produce 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{a}}(t)$
\end_inset

 only if it has more than a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 of the required inputs of each type to produce 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{a}}(t)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\textrm{input}}$
\end_inset

 time steps in a row, in order to model producers' or cautious anticipatory
 behavior.
 In order to satisfy this constraint, if the inventory for an input is 
\begin_inset Formula $x\%$
\end_inset

 below the aforementioned threshold, actual production 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{a}}(t)$
\end_inset

 is reduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\%$
\end_inset

 compared to optimal production 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{Opt}}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 This constraint must be satisfied for each type of input (i.e.
 sectors) involved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lastly, inputs required for production are then drawn from their respective
 inventories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Orders and demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.1.2 orders"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The order/demand module computes the various demands.
 Total demand consists of final demand 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

, intermediate orders 
\begin_inset Formula $O(t)$
\end_inset

 and rebuilding demand 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Final demand 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

 for each region is exogenous and set by the MRIOT.
 Currently, it stays fixed during the simulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Intermediate orders 
\begin_inset Formula $O(t)$
\end_inset

 are decided based on inventories and consists of two parts: the first part
 is the amount of inputs used to produce during the current step, while
 the second is a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{1}{\tau_{\textrm{inv}}}}$
\end_inset

 of the remaining gap with inventory goal.
 Inventory goals are defined as the inventories needed to produce at 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{Opt}}(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In case capital rebuilding has been set as endogenous, only a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{1}{\tau_{\textrm{rebuild}}}}$
\end_inset

 of the remaining rebuilding demand is ordered at each step, so that rebuilding
 is not instantaneous but takes a characteristic time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\textrm{rebuild}}$
\end_inset

.
 Rebuilding demand is used to build back capital stocks and thus restores
 production capacities to their pre-shock levels.
 If capital rebuilding is exogenous, there is no rebuilding demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.1.2 distrib"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distribution module allocates the actual production towards the various
 demands.
 Distribution follows a proportional rationing scheme: if total demand cannot
 be met, intermediate orders 
\begin_inset Formula $O(t)$
\end_inset

, final demand 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

 and rebuilding demand 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 receive actual production according to their share of total demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Overproduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.1.2 overprod"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In ARIO, industries can temporarily increase their production capacity from
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\textrm{Cap}}(t)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\times x^{\textrm{Cap}}(t)$
\end_inset

 when they cannot meet total demand.
 It is a gradual process: when needed, the overproduction factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 can switch from a base value 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{b}$
\end_inset

 (most often 1) up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{\textrm{max}}$
\end_inset

 with an exogenous characteristic time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 The evolution of also depends on a scarcity index, defined as unmet demand
 divided by total demand: it is faster the higher the scarcity index is.
 In the current state of development of BoARIO, overproduction comes at
 no cost for the economic agents: it is limited by the fact that it is not
 an instantaneous process and that it cannot exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{\textrm{max}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Coping behavior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.1.2 coping"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to overproduction, industries can change their suppliers to
 some extent, which introduces more substitutability in ARIO than in a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 IO model.
 As shortages start to appear, demand is still distributed among suppliers
 in the same proportions as before the shock.
 However, as unmet demand grows, suppliers that have not been affected by
 direct impacts (on capital or production) can overproduce and catch demand
 from new buyers.
 Buyers will then marginally shift their orders to producers that can overproduc
e.
 This feature draws on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "guan20_global_suppl_chain_effec_covid_contr_measur"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Qualitative behavior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to present a general overview of the ARIO model, we describe here
 four elementary responses an industry can have following a shock, depending
 on the rebuilding demand and the parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement t
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename imgs/BoARIO-basic-responses.pdf
	width 90text%

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Basic ARIO responses.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.fig:responses"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
a)
\end_layout

\end_inset

When the industry does not have to answer a rebuilding demand, or in the
 recovery case, and no shortage happens (either because the shock is too
 small or the parameters not too constraining).
 The model suffers a loss of production for the duration of the event and
 then slowly regains its production output via the recovery as well as the
 overproduction mechanism.
 A small overshoot to refill possible remaining gaps in inventories can
 be seen before initial equilibrium is found again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
b)
\end_layout

\end_inset

If a shortage happens, it slows down the return of production level to its
 initial amount, possibly extending the recovery period.
 It may also slightly increase the overshoot in production as inventory
 gaps are increased by the longer recovery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
c)
\end_layout

\end_inset

When the industry answers a rebuilding demand, but no shortage happens,
 production rises more sharply due to the increased scarcity created by
 the rebuilding demand.
 Production also continues to increase as long as total demand is not met,
 and starts decreasing when it is met and remaining rebuilding demand and
 inventory gaps are answered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
d)
\end_layout

\end_inset

If a shortage happens, production reduces to match its inventories.
 As long as total demand remains higher than production for the input(s)
 responsible for the shortage, the inventory gap continues to increase and
 production to decrease.
 This stops when production is low enough and received orders are high enough
 so that the gap starts decreasing.
 Production then increases back as in the last phase of c), but sharply
 due to the increased orders to refill inventories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Actual responses can of course be more complex, as interrelations between
 industries create feedbacks.
 As such, shortages can occur earlier or later, at several different times,
 and decrease production to a greater extent.
\end_layout

