name "app1.3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Building agent-based models such as ARIO requires a trade-off between the
 simplicity of the mechanisms described and the amount of parameters to
 calibrate, and therefore the transparency of modeled impacts.
 Considering both the conceptual model or its implementation, several hypotheses
 are made, leading to important limits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.3.1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Production is Leontief-based: no substitution possible between different
 inputs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Goods produced in the same sector but in different locations are perfect
 substitutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Industries can always hire (for overproduction).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Industries and households can always buy goods (no prices, no wages, no
 budget).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.3.2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are multiple parameters, which are difficult to calibrate, notably
 because of a lack of empirical data (inventory size, characteristic times,
 \SpecialChar ldots
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The model does not account for price variations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The implementation does (yet) not account for the role of labor (notably
 the reduction in production capacity due to workers not being able to work
 during the event).
\end_layout

